# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-rules-football-in-china
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2002-australian-football-international-cup] The **2002 Australian Football International Cup** was the inaugural international Australian rules football tournament held in Melbourne, Australia in 2002.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2002-australian-football-international-cup] 11 nations participated from around the world and the tournament was officiated by the International Australian Football Council.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2002-australian-football-international-cup] Ireland won the tournament, finishing undefeated and victorious over Papua New Guinea in the Grand Final on 23 August at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2002-australian-football-international-cup] A 22 player All-International squad was named, however names were unplaced and not allocated to any specific field position.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The **2005 Australian Football International Cup** was the second time that the Australian Football International Cup tournament, an international Australian rules football competition was held.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The event was hosted by both Melbourne and Wangaratta, Australia, in 2005.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2005-australian-football-international-cup] 10 nations participated following the late withdrawal of both Nauru and Denmark and the introduction of Spain.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2005-australian-football-international-cup] All sides were scheduled to play 4 games, after which the top 4 sides played off in semi-finals for a berth in the Grand Final decider.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The Grand Final was between Papua New Guinea and New Zealand.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Both sides went through the tournament undefeated.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2005-australian-football-international-cup] It was played as a curtain raiser to an official Australian Football League premiership season match and was replayed on Fox Sports (Australia) and the Fox Footy Channel.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2005-australian-football-international-cup] New Zealand were crowned international champions for the first time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The grand final was replayed on Fox Sports (Australia) and the Fox Footy Channel.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The best and fairest medal was awarded to New Zealand's James Bowden.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Like the All-Australian Team in the Australian Football League, a team selected from the best players in the International Cup was selected.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Team members were unplaced and not allocated to any specific field position.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The **2008 Australian Football International Cup** was the third time the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition, has been contested.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] It was scheduled for 2008 (as part of the 150th year celebrations of Australian Football), with 16 nations competing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The tournament was hosted by both Melbourne and Warrnambool in Victoria, Australia between 27 August and 6 September, with a single match additionally played in Geelong.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Like previous tournaments, the competition was open to men's teams with strict nationality eligibility rules.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The Grand Final was played between New Zealand and Papua New Guinea.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea were victorious by 8 points with a goal kicked after the siren.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Like the Grand Final in previous years, the match was played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain raiser to the 2008 AFL Second qualifying Final which attracted a crowd of 76,703 spectators.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] However unlike previous tournaments, the final was not televised.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL later indicated that a regional round and semi-finals would be held in Warrnambool.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL indicated that unlike earlier cups, it would likely be split into two divisions, a premier division and development division, with some discussion as to whether the eligibility rules could be loosened for the development division, to enable more countries to participate.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Leagues were given the opportunity to nominate which they would prefer, with eight in each division being an initial target.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Ultimately, this idea was dropped, with the sixteen teams being seeded into four pools.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In December 2007, it was announced that Melbourne and Warrnambool would co-host the two division event, with Melbourne matches to be played mainly in Royal Park North.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Several potential new sides were announced by the AFL, including an Israeli-Palestine combination supported by the Peres Centre for Peace, China and India.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The USA Women's team announced an intention to send a squad to play against Australia and possibly Papua New Guinea.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Additionally Canada and England announced their intentions to send Under 17s squads.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] As a result, there was speculation over an inaugural women's and under 17 divisions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] However the AFL denied these divisions in favour of a senior men's competition only.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In response, and with the Barassi International Australian Football Youth Tournament being cancelled, British and Canadian junior teams had to organise their own tours and matches against Australian schools.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Despite both international teams being in Australia at the same time, they did not play against each other.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The US women's team announced a 2009 tour instead.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL confirmed in July 2008 that sixteen nations will compete.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In addition, there will be friendly matches played between Melbourne-based migrant community teams under the names "Team Africa" and "Team Asia", as well as the Tongan side which was unable to commit to the full tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Also despite a previous appearance, the Spain Bulls will not be competing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The world team was selected based on player performance in the pool rounds only.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2008-australian-football-international-cup] India, China, the Peace Team and Finland all missed representation in the team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The **2011 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the **AFL International Cup 2011** or **IC11**) was the fourth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between 12 and 27 August 2011 by 18 nations, with games played in both Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Two matches were played as curtain raisers to AFL premiership matches, USA vs South Africa at Stadium Australia and the IC Grand Final at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Ireland won its second men's championship, and the inaugural women's championship (Ryan Aslett Cup).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] 17 of these clubs represented single nations, and one (the Peres Team for Peace) represented both Israel and the Palestinian Territories.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The first round of matches was played with modified rules, most significantly the reduction of game length to two-quarters, in the same manner as the 2011 NAB Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 1, the best two teams from each Group were regrouped into four groups of three teams, based on Win-Draw-Loss performance and Percentage in Round 1, all within a larger group known as Division 1.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These teams would remain in contention for the International Cup title.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The remaining six were regrouped in the same way, into two subgroups of Division 2.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These teams would compete for a secondary prize.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Division 1 teams played one match against each team in their respective groups.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Division 2 teams played one match against each team in their respective groups, as well as a single "cross-over" match against a team in the opposite group.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 2, the teams were once again re-seeded based on their performance in the previous round; the teams in Division 1 were seeded in positions 1-12, and the teams in Division 2 in positions 13–18.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These matches were played at the same time as the final round 2 Division 2 matches; the Division 2 teams did not participate in this round.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] In the opening round of the Women's International Cup, the five teams played each other once, over the course of 10 days.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 1, Australia, the lowest ranked team in the competition based on points and percentage, was eliminated and finished in 5th place.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The remaining four clubs will compete in the finals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The **2014 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the AFL International Cup 2014 or **IC14**) was the fifth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between Saturday August 9 to Saturday August 23, with games played in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] All three previous champions (Ireland, New Zealand and Papua New Guinea) participated in the tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] There are 18 nations competing in the 2014 Tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Of these, 15 competed in the previous tournament; Indonesia and Pakistan make their debuts, while Finland return having previously competed in 2008.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The teams were seeded into three pools of six to decide which teams would play each other, though all teams will be ranked on a single ladder.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The top four teams at the end of Day 3 progress to the International Cup Semi-finals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The other teams will play another match, depending on their ladder position, with those results added to the Ladder to decide Day 5 matchups.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The 5th to 12th-placed teams will play in Division 1 for the remainder of the tournament, and the 13th-placed team onwards will play in Division 2.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] For the second consecutive time, there was a concurrent Women's tournament alongside the Men's competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Seven teams participated from five countries - the United States and Canada both fielded two teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Each team played four matches across five matchdays.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Matches played on Saturday 16 August - the "Community Round" of the tournament - were played as curtain-raisers to other amateur Metropolitan and Country football matches to be confirmed; all other games in the round-robin were held at Royal Park, Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] After the round-robin tournament, the last placed team was eliminated.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The other six teams played one extra match to decide the final placings, with the top two teams on the ladder playing in the Women's International Cup Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The **2017 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the AFL International Cup 2017 or IC17) was the sixth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, a triennial international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between 5–19 August 2017, with games played in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] All three previous men's tournament champions (Ireland, New Zealand and Papua New Guinea) participated in the tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Previous women's winners (Ireland and Canada) also competed in the tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea achieved its 3rd men's title and Ireland achieved its 2nd women's title.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The 2017 AFL International Cup was played in Melbourne from 5 to 19 August, with 18 men's teams and eight women's teams competing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The European Crusaders was a combined team made up of women from Britain, Croatia, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Poland and Sweden.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] In the table below, the numbers in parentheses refer to the team's Unofficial World Rankings by *World Footy News* prior to the competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] For the first time, the men's fixture was played across two divisions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Division One played four matches against other teams within the division and were ranked from one to ten, with finals to follow between the top two placed teams on the ladder, the third and fourth placed teams, and so on.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The men's Division Two competition and the women's competition saw teams split into two pools of four with each team playing matches against the three opponents in their pool before competing in semi-finals and grand finals based on finishing positions within the pool.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The women's grand final was played at Etihad Stadium as a curtain-raiser to the Round 22 clash between Carlton and Hawthorn.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The men's grand final was played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain-raiser to the Round 22 match between Collingwood and Geelong.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The majority of the matches were played at Royal Park in the Melbourne suburb of Parkville.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The inclusion of a "Community Round" allowed matches to be played as curtain-raisers to local suburban, amateur and country matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Additionally, the International Cup introduced a "School Round" to be played on 9 August, with games played at suburban and country schools.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Fixtures for the tournament were released by the AFL on 18 July 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] The **2019 AFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Richmond Football Club and Greater Western Sydney Giants at the Melbourne Cricket Ground on 28 September 2019.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] It was the 124th annual grand final of the Australian Football League (formerly Victorian Football League), staged to determine the premiers for the 2019 AFL season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] The match, attended by 100,014 spectators, was won by Richmond by a margin of 89 points, marking the club's twelfth VFL/AFL premiership and their second in three seasons.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Richmond's Dustin Martin won the Norm Smith Medal as the player judged best on ground.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Richmond suffered misfortune during the first half of the season, with several of their star players sidelined due to injury – including star defender Alex Rance, and young stars in Jack Higgins, Sydney Stack and Jack Graham.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] At the conclusion of Round 14, the Tigers were ninth on the ladder with an average 7–6 win–loss record; however, they did not lose again in the home-and-away season, winning their last nine games to finish third with a 16–6 record.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] The Tigers advanced directly to the preliminary final after a 47-point victory over Brisbane in the qualifying final; then, in the preliminary final, overcame a 21-point half time deficit to defeat Geelong by 19 points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Greater Western Sydney started season 2019 having been eliminated from the 2018 season in the semi-finals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] The club lost co-captain Callan Ward to an ACL injury early in the season, a season-ending injury to star midfielder Stephen Coniglio later in the year.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] A strong start to the year saw the Giants placed second after Round 11, but indifferent form and a 5–6 record in the second half of the year, saw the Giants qualify for the finals in sixth with a 13–9 win–loss record.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] It was just the second time since the introduction of the AFL final eight system in 2000 that a team reached the grand final without finishing inside the top four, after the Bulldogs' 2016 victory.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] The teams met twice during the home-and-away season; first in round 3 at Giants Stadium when the Giants thrashed Richmond by 49 points, and then in round 17 at the MCG when the Tigers won by 27 points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] It was Richmond's 23rd grand final appearance, and second in three years; and it was the first grand final appearance for Greater Western Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] The sides had previously contested one final, the 2017 preliminary final won by Richmond by 36 points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] As the higher-ranked team, Richmond wore its full home kit, and GWS wore its predominantly white clash guernsey with white shorts.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Richmond was an overwhelming favourite to win, with bookmakers offering odds of $1.44 for a Richmond win compared with $3.25 for a Giants win.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] With an average audience of 2.197 million across the five major capital cities, this was the lowest-rating AFL Grand Final on free-to-air television since OzTAM began recording television ratings in 2001.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Tones and I performed "The Kids Are Coming" and "Dance Monkey", and was followed by Dean Lewis, who performed "Be Alright" and "Waves".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] John Williamson also performed Waltzing Matilda.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Paul Kelly performed "Leaps and Bounds" and "Dumb Things".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Mike Brady also performed "Up There Cazaly".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Conrad Sewell performed the Australian National Anthem "Advance Australia Fair".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Richmond chose Maureen Hafey – the widow of legendary Richmond coach Tom Hafey – as their ambassador to carry the premiership cup onto the field, while GWS chose Kevin Sheedy – their first-ever coach.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Hafey also presented the trophy to Trent Cotchin and Damien Hardwick during the on-field award ceremony.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] The opening term of the grand final was a tough and low-scoring battle, with neither team scoring a goal in the first twenty minutes of the match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Giants spearhead Jeremy Cameron scored the opening goal of the grand final at the 20-minute mark before two late goals—from Dustin Martin at the 24-minute mark and Daniel Rioli right on the quarter-time siren—saw the Tigers take a seven-point lead at quarter time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Richmond was the stronger team in the second quarter.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] They scored five unanswered goals in a dominant quarter; Jack Riewoldt goaled at the four-minute mark of the term, followed by Martin's second goal at the seven-and-a-half minute mark.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Tom Lynch scored two minutes later before Riewoldt finished the half with another two goals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Greater Western Sydney was held to just four behinds in the second quarter, and Richmond held a 35-point lead at half time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Richmond sealed the premiership with a dominant third quarter in which it scored five goals to one.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Lynch kicked his second goal at the five-minute mark before Martin kicked his third in the eighth minute.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Marlion Pickett scored his only goal of the afternoon at the 11th minute, and Kane Lambert scored two minutes after.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] The Giants finally broke a run of 11 consecutive Richmond goals with a Jacob Hopper goal at the 25-minute mark of the quarter, before Ivan Soldo goaled right on the three-quarter-time siren.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] The margin was 62 points in favour of the Tigers at three quarter time, and the premiership was now beyond doubt.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] In the final quarter, Richmond again scored five goals and conceded only one.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] The Giants scored their third and final goal of the game early in the final quarter by Harry Himmelberg second minute.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Shai Bolton scored his first goal of the day for Richmond at the ninth minute, followed by Riewoldt's fourth goal.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Richmond skipper Trent Cotchin goaled at the 23-minute mark and was followed soon after by Martin, who also scored his fourth goal.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Riewoldt kicked the final goal only moments before the siren to increase the final margin to 89 points, the third-highest margin in a grand final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] It was Richmond's greatest winning margin in a grand final, surpassing its 81-point victory against Collingwood in 1980.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] By unanimous selection – 15 out of 15 possible votes – Dustin Martin was awarded his second Norm Smith Medal after having won it in 2017, making him the fourth player to win multiple Norm Smith Medals after Gary Ayres, Andrew McLeod and Luke Hodge.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] No other player garnered more than 6 votes, but Bachar Houli finished second as he did in 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] The teams were announced on 26 September 2019.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Richmond made one change to the side, with Jack Graham dropping out of the side due to a shoulder injury he suffered in the preliminary final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] He was the first player to make his senior debut in a grand final since Keith Batchelor for Collingwood in 1952.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Richmond fielded sixteen of the twenty-two players who had been part of its premiership team in 2017: Pickett, Tom Lynch, Shai Bolton, Ivan Soldo, Jayden Short and Liam Baker were the new players, and Rance, Grigg, Graham, Jacob Townsend, Dan Butler and Kamdyn McIntosh were the six missing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] Greater Western Sydney recalled Toby Greene and Lachie Whitfield, who missed their preliminary final win due to suspension and injury respectively, into their side, with Lachlan Keeffe and Ian Hill omitted to make way.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] GWS also was missing former Richmond rising star Brett Deledio, after he had been injured earlier in the finals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/2019-afl-grand-final] The umpiring panel, comprising three field umpires, four boundary umpires, two goal umpires and an emergency in each position is given below.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] Interest in Australian football in China received a boost after the AFL, the premier professional football competition in Australia, invested in an AFL exhibition match in Shanghai in 2010, and followed up with an AFL academy in 2011.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] Further investment has followed from other interests including the construction of a dedicated AFL oval in Tianjin in 2011.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The AFL Commission designed AFLX in 2017 as a means to promote the sport in China.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] It scheduled a series of AFL Premiership matches was played at Jiangwan Stadium from 2017 to 2019, the first outside of Pacific, which attracted an average attendance of 10,073.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The local state TV network began broadcasting matches from Australia in 2016.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The 2019 AFL Grand Final was watched by a record 5.67 million viewers.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] Star Sports has since broadcast AFL there.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] There are a number of senior clubs spread throughout China, including in the bigger cities of Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou and Tianjin, as well as Auskick programs in other cities such as Suzhou, Jiangsu province.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The national team, composed solely of Chinese nationals, is known as the China (Dragons or Reds).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] It won the Asian Australian Football Championships All-Asia Cup in 2017 and 2018 and achieved its best international result of 13th at the 2017 Australian Football International Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] Chinese Australians have been playing Australian rules football since the late 19th century.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] In 1882, 17-year-old Henry George Chin Kit made his debut for the Ironbark Football Club against Charing Cross in the Bendigo Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The Ballarat Chinese Football Premiership was covered extensively between 1892 and 1896, in local newspapers.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] A widely published 1939 editorial highlighted a very positive response to the game from a group of visiting Chinese delegates, one of which proposed that China should adopt the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The first recorded match in Hong Kong was in 1939 played by the Royal Australian Navy.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] Matches were played by Australian Naval Reservists in 1940, there was hope that local Chinese would take up the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] In July 1940, a match was played at Kowloon at the Police Club grounds.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] In 1984 the South Australian National Football League announced a plan to sell rights to its matches to China to an audience of around 70 million including translations.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The Hong Kong Dragons Australian expatriate team was formed in 1990, and have been one of Asia's most successful Australian rules football clubs since this time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The Dragons play against other Asian teams regularly and have competed at all Asian Australian Football Championships to date.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] Auskick, the Australian football program for juniors, grew in Hong Kong in the early 2000s after two Victorian expatriate families managed to secure official support and equipment from the AFL in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The Dragons also coordinate an Auskick juniors program.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] Players trained at the iconic grounds at Happy Valley as well as the Australian International School Hong Kong (AISHK).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] A junior program called the Gobi Desert AFL existed at a primary school in Hami, Xinjiang in the 1990s, but this has now disappeared.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] A club was established in Shanghai under the name of the Shanghai Tigers in 2002.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The Tigers have a playing list consisting mainly of expatriate Australians, with some British, American and South African players as well.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] Australian rules was first played in Beijing in 2004, with the foundation of the Australian Expatriate team, the Beijing Bombers.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] In city of Suzhou in 2007, 18 schools had introduced the sport into their curriculum.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The sister city relationship between Tianjin and Melbourne saw the beginnings of football development in 2005.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] By 2007, a development organisation called the AFL China had been formed, with Tianjin Normal University having two Australian football teams at its main campuses.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The Tianjin program was sponsored by the Melbourne Football Club and the Melbourne City Council, through links formed by former Melbourne Lord Mayor John So.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The Beijing Bombers played an annual China Cup series against the other Australian expatriate team the Shanghai Tigers, as well as starting a 3-team metro league known as the Beijing AFL in 2009.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] Australian football began in Macau in 2009, with the introduction of Auskick and matches at the International School of Macau.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The Macau Lightning Australian expatriate senior team debuted in 2010, with matches against the Hong Kong Dragons and Pokfulam Vikings.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] They made their first Asian Championships appearance in Shanghai in October 2010, but failed to win any matches at the tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] A second Australian expatriate team in the Pokfulam region of Hong Kong was in existence in 2010, playing as the Pokfulam Vikings and conducting some matches against the Dragons.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The Guangzhou Scorpions Australian expatriate team was formed in 2010, playing matches against the Hong Kong Dragons and Macau Lightning.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] In late 2011 into early 2012 Darrell Egan Founded the Dongguan Panther Blues team at a middle school in Humen Dongguan.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The team is also known in Australia as the China Blues consists of 15 to 18 years old student players, with some old school players up to the age of 20.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The team went on to play Chinese teams of locals which formed in mid 2013 and is now coached under team's original captain Lin Honghue (Leighton Lin).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] Darrell Egan now acts as the team's Australian Liaison manager.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The Dongguan Panther Blues established the first Chinese team of locals in China in 2014.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] Carlton Blues player Wally Koochew (See Below) being a pioneer as the first Chinese player in VFL/AFL history the Dongguan Blues team are also the pioneers in China.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] In 2016 Port Adelaide FC signed born and raised 2014 International Cup captain Chen Shaoliang to its International Scholarship list Shaoliang played reserves matches with Port Adelaide in the SANFL however was not elevated to the club's AFL list.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] A representative team mainly consisting of expat Australians in China has competed under the names China Blues and China Reds in International fixtures and Asian AFL Championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] The first national representative team composed entirely of Chinese nationals appeared as the China Red Demons at the 2008 Australian Football International Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-china/australian-rules-football-in-china] Bo Gee Lu, a native of Guangdong played Australian Rules Football while studying at the University of Adelaide and went on to represent China with significant esteem in a number of International Cups, mostly as a midfielder/forward or pinch hitting in the Ruck.
